The paper deals with modeling and analyzing a market with strategic buyers and nonstrategic vendors, which involves game theory and mechanism design. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory and Mechanism Design) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes an algorithm to compute prices that are rational and fair, which involves optimization and computational complexity, making cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also discusses the use of valuations and preferences of buyers, which involves artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with pricing and market efficiency, which involves economics and econometrics, making cs.EC (Economics and Computation) a possible sub-category.
